|style="font-weight:bold;"|<poem>
Fratelli d'Italia,
l'Italia s'è desta,
dell'elmo di Scipio
s'è cinta la testa.
Dov'è la Vittoria?
Le porga la chioma,
ché schiava di Roma
Iddio la creò.<br> (repeat all)</poem>
|<poem>Brothers of [[Italy]],
Italy has woken,
bound [[Scipio Africanus|Scipio]]'s helmet
Upon her head.{{#tag:ref|The original Italian text reads "Italy has woken, of Scipio's helmet she [here the verb "cingere" is used, but it has no translation in English] the head."|group=N}}
Where is [[Victoria (mythology)|Victory]]?
Let her bow down,{{#tag:ref|"Le porga la chioma" can also be more literally translated as "Let her tender her hair to Rome" or "Tender her hair", referring to the ancient custom of cutting off the hair of slaves.|group=N}}
Because [as a] slave of [[Ancient Rome|Rome]]
[[God]] created her.<br>(repeat all)</poem> 
